  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <h2>What an AS 3660.2 annual inspection covers.</h2>
      <div style="max-width: 65rem;">

        <h3>The standard method.</h3>
        <p>
          AS 3660.2-2017 (Termite management Part 2: In and around existing
          buildings and structures) sets out a specific inspection
          methodology. It&rsquo;s not a walk-around. It&rsquo;s a systematic
          audit of every cellulose-bearing zone in the building with
          documented findings.
        </p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Sub-floor / stump base inspection</strong> &mdash; every joist, bearer, stump, ant-cap. Moisture-meter readings. Mud-tunnel scan. Particularly important on high-set Nightcliff and Casuarina stock.</li>
          <li><strong>Roof void inspection</strong> &mdash; every truss, top plate, rafter, fascia, eave. We schedule early-morning slots to avoid 50&deg;C mid-afternoon Darwin roof-void temperatures.</li>
          <li><strong>Perimeter inspection</strong> &mdash; slab edge, weep holes, brick courses, weatherboard joints, slab penetrations.</li>
          <li><strong>Chemical-barrier integrity check</strong> &mdash; sample points around the perimeter to verify the chemical band is still active. Test 4&ndash;6 points per house in Darwin.</li>
          <li><strong>Garden + outbuildings</strong> &mdash; sheds, fences, retaining walls, landscape timbers, mulched beds.</li>
          <li><strong>Interior wet areas</strong> &mdash; bathrooms, kitchen, laundry. Termites love wet timber.</li>
          <li><strong>Written report</strong> &mdash; AS 3660.2 format with photos, readings, recommendations.</li>
        </ol>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Why annual isn&rsquo;t a black-letter law but matters legally.</h3>
        <p>
          AS 3660 isn&rsquo;t legislation but it&rsquo;s the standard the courts
          use to decide whether &ldquo;reasonable care&rdquo; was taken. If a
          home gets eaten by termites and the owner skipped inspections, the
          insurance won&rsquo;t pay AND there&rsquo;s no recourse against
          previous owners, building inspectors, pest treaters or the
          warranty insurer. Annual inspection is the documented &ldquo;reasonable
          care&rdquo; threshold. Skipping it is taking the entire termite risk
          onto your own balance sheet.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Top End-specific adjustments to the standard schedule.</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>High-set pre-1990 stock</strong> &mdash; 6-monthly recommended (sub-floor humidity is wet for 6&ndash;9 months/yr)</li>
          <li><strong>Bushland-boundary rural acreage</strong> &mdash; 6-monthly recommended (Mastotermes ingress pressure)</li>
          <li><strong>Coastal Nightcliff / Casuarina foreshore</strong> &mdash; annual + perimeter chemical-barrier test at every visit (faster degradation)</li>
          <li><strong>Renovated stock</strong> &mdash; annual + post-renovation reinstatement check if barriers were disturbed</li>
          <li><strong>Modern Palmerston slab-on-ground</strong> &mdash; annual sufficient if reticulation under warranty and physical barriers intact</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">What you get with our annual inspection package.</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>AS 3660.2-compliant written report with photos, readings and recommendations within 48h</li>
          <li>Chemical-barrier status (current life remaining or expired)</li>
          <li>Form 16 paperwork review where applicable</li>
          <li>Next-inspection scheduled (we send reminders)</li>
          <li>Same-pest-controller continuity (you see the same inspector year-on-year so trend data is comparable)</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
